Introduction¶

Gapminder is an independet Swedish foundation which dedicated itself to providing reliable statistics for almost every aspect of global development. They're self stated goal is to provide free to explore datasets for everybody to promota a better understanding of the world on a fact basis. Therefore, they collaborate with universities, the UN, NGOs and public agencies to gather reliable datasets and make them available to the public in one place.

For this project I chose to compare the economic and welfare development of different regions from different parts of the world. I chose to build a dataset based on the following measures:

economic measure:

  • GDP per capita. It is calculated using the gross domestic product of country divided by its population. Aditionally, the values are adjusted for differences in purchasing power

health related measures:

  • life expectancy: the life expectancy is defined as the average amount of years a newborn child is expected to live if current mortality patterns were to stay the same.
  • child mortality: defined as the total amount of death of children under 5 years of age per 1000 live births.
  • birth rate: defined as the average number of children to be born to a family.

Each dataset contains data for 184 different countries for the years 1800 until 2018. With the help of the above mentioned measures, I'd like to explore regional differences in development, each measures influence on welfare as well as their correlation among each other.

The following packages are used to explore the dataset:

Looks like each dataset has one column with a list of all countries followed by one column for each year containing the respective measurements. In order to be able to compare the influence of the different measures, it is necessary to merge each individual dataset into one big dataset. In their current shape, this is not possible. I envision the columns of the merged dataset so look like this: {country, year, measure1, measure2,...}. To achieve this, it is necessary to group all years to one year column and all values to one value column.

  1. Change properties of each dataset

Pandas .melt() function allows us to do exactly this.

Let's start with the gdp_per_cap dataset:

In [8]:

  1. Merge Datasets
In [15]:
# create a list containing all dataframes
measures = [gdp_per_cap, life_exp, child_mortality, birth_rate]

# merge them into one dataframe. the argument how=inner' ensures that the merged dataframe
# only contains countries for which data exists in all 4 datasets.
df = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, how='inner', on=['geo', 'year']), measures)

(Disclaimer: I adapted the solution to merging multiple datasets at once from this stackoverflow post https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44327999/python-pandas-merge-multiple-dataframes)

4.3 Define a function which tells Pandas which value to assign to each country, depending on the continent.

In [21]:
def assign_name(df):
    if df['country'] in europe:
        val = 'Europe'
    elif df['country'] in africa:
        val = 'Africa'
    elif df['country'] in asia:
        val = 'Asia'
    elif df['country'] in ozeania:
        val = 'Ozeania'
    elif df['country'] in north_america:
        val = 'North America'
    else:
        val = 'South America'
    return val

4.4 Finally, create a new column in the DataFrame containing each countrys respective continent.

Research Question 1: Are there differences in the development of the GDP per capita across different continents?¶

To adress this question, we need to first assign a variable for each continent where we filter the DataFrame by the respective continent. We can do this using Pandas build in .query() function. On top of that, we need to group each query by year and calculate the mean value for each measure in each year. Long story short, the Code which does the job for me looks like this:

In [37]:
europe_df = df.query('continent in "Europe"').groupby('year').mean().reset_index()
europe_df.head()

mean GDP per capita in 1900: 1840.61
standard deviation in 1900: 1562.08
mean GDP per capita in 2018: 17919.24
standard deviation in 2018: 19595.64

The line graph shows that the GDP per capita was roughly the same for all continents in the 19th century. Only then do changes in economic growth start to kick in and from the 1950's onward, the economic growth is almost exponential for some continents. However, it has to be noted, that not all continents participated equally in economic growth and thus walfare inequalities worsend ever since the beginning of the 20th century. This becomes clear when comparing the global standard deviation in 1900 (1,562) and 2018 (19,595). Europe's economy is currenctly by far the strongest, followed by Asia and North America, Africa being the taillight. Also interesting to note is the fact, that the 3 wealthiest continents are all located North of the Equator, whereas the 3 poorest continents all have the majority of their landmass South of the Equator.

life_exp_19th_century = df.query('year >= 1800').query('year < 1900')['life_exp']
print('Average life expectancy in 19th century: {} years'.format(round(life_exp_19th_century.mean(), 2)))

life_exp_21st_century = df.query('year >= 2000').query('year <=2018')['life_exp']

Average life expectancy in 19th century: 31.94 years
Average life expectancy in 21st century: 69.93 years

Regarding the average life expectancy, each continent experienced an increase starting at the turn of the 19th century. Although there are differences among continents, the average life expectancy doubled for most continents compared to their value in the 19th century. The global mean life expectancy was just 31.9 years int the 19th century and the global average is currently 69.9 years for the 21st century.

(Side note: Clearly visible are also two major dips resulting in the millions of casualties during the course of WW1 and WW2.)

Reseach Question 6: Is there a correlation between the GDP per capita and life expectancy?¶

life expectancy is the dependent variable whereas GDP per capita is the independent variable

In [51]:
set_matplotlib_formats('retina')
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.scatter(df['gdp_per_capita'], df['life_exp'], color='teal')
plt.title('Fig.5: correlation between GDP per capita and life expectancy')
plt.xlabel('GDP per capita')
plt.ylabel('life expectancy')
plt.axis([0, 50000, 0, 90]);

I limited the x-axis to 50,000 to prevent outliers from heavily distorting the graph to the right. The scatter plot shows a steep, moderate positive logarithmic distribution of data points. This indicates a positive correlation between the two variables. Let's calculate the correlation coefficient to test this observation for statistical significance. Given the fact that this dataset contains 42,267 data points, the pearsonr coefficient and the p-value should be reasonably reliable for testing statistic significance.

In [52]:
pearsonr(df['gdp_per_capita'], df['life_exp'])
Out[52]:
(0.5731051857092431, 0.0)

The first number of the output is the pearson correlation coefficient. The correlation coefficient (0.57) is moderate and thus indicates a moderate probability for a positive correlation between the GDP per capita and the life expectancy. However, this does not mean, that an increase in one variable definately results in an increase in the other variable as one or both variables could be biased by a, yet unknown, third variable.

Research Question 7: Is there a correlation between life expectancy and child mortality?¶

Life expectancy and child mortality are both variables which by common sense should depend on the same thing - the access to medication and improvement of hygienic conditions. The average child mortality can therefore be expected to decrease as the life expectancy increases. Let's have a closer look at both variables to examine this hypothesis.

In [53]:
set_matplotlib_formats('retina')
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.scatter(df['life_exp'], df['child_mortality'], color='teal')
plt.title('Fig.6: correlation between life expectancy and child mortality')
plt.xlabel('life expectancy')
plt.ylabel('child mortality');

And indeed, from a pure visual investigation, a negative correlation seems to be obvious. Maybe the pearson correlation coefficient can confirm this obseration.

In [54]:
pearsonr(df['life_exp'], df['child_mortality'])
Out[54]:
(-0.9417413485419234, 0.0)

The pearson correlation coefficient is -0.94, thus indicating a high probability for a negative correlation between both variables. Although again, it has to be stated, that the pure calculation of a correlation coefficient is no sufficient proof of causation as one or both variables could be biased by a third, yet unknown, variable.

Conclusion¶

To summarize, this report explored the development of economic and health related variales between 1800 and 2018. Furthermore, correlation among these variables was explored.

Regarding the development of the GDP per capita, things started out on a rather similar level in 1800 with huge differences emerging from the beginning of the 20th century. The average life expectancy doubled for each continent over the past 200 years but differences among continents are also present. The average child mortality and birth rate both decreased over time with the difference of this development starting roughly half a century earlier for child mortality.

Research questions 6 and 7 led to the assumption of a high probability for a positive correlation between GDP per capita and life expectancy and a negative correlation between life expectancy and child mortality. However, those results should be taken with a grain of salt as the pure calculation of a correlation coefficient is not sufficient to prove causation between both variables.
